To clarify further the origin of the different noise terms, we performed the same series of tests on the SC2 device in which the passivating i-a-Si:H layer between the bulk n-c-Si and n-a-Si:H layer was omitted. In fact, this device was essential to our initial motivation to understand if noise spectroscopy can characterize trap states on the heterointerface of c-Si and the ability of i-a-Si:H to passivate it. To our surprise, no quantitative difference was detected between the spectra generated by the SC1 and SC2 devices as shown in Fig. S5 of the supplementary material. Despite the obvious effect on VOC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$V_{{OC}}$$\end{document}, the absence of the front-facing i-a-Si:H layer does not appear to produce an observable effect upon the noise spectra indicating that the noise features seen do not relate to the passivation quality or to the transport properties in the i-a-Si:H layer.

